  publisher = {OSF},
  urldate = {2025-10-23},
  abstract = {Emotional similarity in romantic couples has mostly been studied by examining whether emotional valence of both partners covaries over time, yielding one similarity score per couple. However, emotional experience is multidimensional and emotional similarity will change over contexts. Moreover, strangers that show little initial similarity might become more similar when experiencing similar contexts (context effect), raising the question whether being in a relationship actually adds similarity (couple effect) on top of context. Here we investigate the contribution of context versus couple effects in partner's emotional similarity, while embracing the multidimensional nature of emotional experience by assessing momentary emotional profile similarity scores. In two independent datasets, we compared romantic partners to strangers and detected which contextual factors predict momentary similarity scores using regression trees. Results reveal that romantic partners are indeed more emotionally similar than strangers, even when accounting for the identified contextual factors, amongst others, valence and contact with partner.},
